Mexico's Hirving Lozano sent shock waves through the Mexican capital on Sunday when he scored the winning goal against Germany in the two teams' opening game of the 2018 World Cup. Mexico's Network of Seismic Monitoring, Analysis and Geological Investigation (SIMMSA) wrote on Twitter that it recorded an artificial earthquake in Mexico City in the 35th minute of the match. Read more: World Cup 2018: Can Joachim Löw keep faith with old guard after Mexico loss? The quake, it added, was possibly caused by "massive jumps" throughout the city in response to Lozano's goal. Mexico went on to win the game in the Russian capital Moscow against the defending world champions 1-0. The shock win was the country's first against Germany at any World Cup.